div.div:
Eren and his companions in the 104th are assigned to the newly-formed Levi Squad, whose assignment is to keep Eren and Historia safe given Eren's newly-discovered power and Historia's knowledge and pedigree. Levi and Erwin have good reason to be concerned, because the priest of the Church that Hanji had hidden away was found tortured to death, making it clear that the Military Police are involved with the cover-up. Things get more harrowing when the MPs make a move on Erwin and the Levi Squad narrowly avoids capture. Eren is also having problems with his Titan transformation, and a deadly killer has been hired to secure Eren and Historia, one Levi knows all too well from his youth.
(Source: Anime News Network)

In the beginning, an "orb" is cast unto Earth. "It" can do two things: change into the form of the thing that stimulates "it"; and come back to life after death. "It" morphs from orb to rock, then to wolf, and finally to boy, but roams about like a newborn who knows nothing. As a boy, "it" becomes Fushi.
Through encounters with human kindness, Fushi not only gains survival skills but grows as a "person". But his journey is darkened by the inexplicable and destructive enemy Nokker and cruel partings with the people he loves.
(Source: Crunchyroll)

Komamoto Kyota is a high school boy who dotes on his 3-year-old sister. His parents both work, so he handles all the housework and childcare at home. Akiyama Sumi is a beautiful, smart, but solitary girl whose intimidating presence keeps everyone at arm's length. When Kyota went to his sister's kindergarten entrance ceremony, he found Sumi there with flushed cheeks, snapping pictures like a pro photographer. "Gosh, how adorable...... she is!" They became friends and gradually grew closer as they learned that they are both taking care of younger siblings. They cook together, help each other pick up the kids from kindergarten, and go on holiday outings. Yes, their relationship is truly that of "mommy's friend." A romantic comedy about child-raising!
(Source: Gagaga Bunko, translated)
Shaberanai Kurusu-san, Kokoro no Uchi wa Suki de Ippai.
